This thesis presents the design and implementation of _TradeTracker_, a mobile and web application that is an all-in-one tool for trading card game collectors and players, focusing on the methodologies and technologies employed throughout development.
Using Agile and Scrum practices such as frequent stand-up meetings, iterative sprints, and continuous integration of user feedback, we emphasized adaptability and collaboration through the development of the project.
Additionally, the thesis serves to evaluate the effectiveness of this approach, highlighting both the benefits and challenges encountered during development.

Trading card game (TCG) collectors have many things to keep track of when managing their collection, including determining which cards are part of which particular sets, where their cards are stored, and the ever-changing card price market.
_TradeTracker_ will facilitate some of these arduous tasks, such as quickly querying if a collector owns a given card instead of checking a myriad of binders and boxes.
Instead of manually updating a giant spreadsheet, a collector can effortlessly scan cards using their phone's camera and log them into a virtual collection, which they can sort, filter, and seamlessly manage.
By leveraging external card marketplaces, _TradeTracker_ approximates the value of any given card, allowing collectors to quickly determine the value of their cards and their collection as a whole.

_TradeTracker_ allows users to interact with each other, including the ability to request and offer cards to trade with others.
If two users agree to trade, they can message each other to choose a safe place to meet and make the exchange.
Users can also host and find local events through the app, fostering growing communities in this hobby.
In summary, _TradeTracker_ is a comprehensive tool that streamlines the process of managing, trading, and value-estimating trading cards, empowering collectors to interact with one another and become more involved in their communities.
